<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-308-890  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 308 890.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 29 1989 v23 n22 p41(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Exploring options for CIM. (computer-integrated manufacturing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Major manufacturing executives speaking at a briefing sponsored byForth Shift, a software vendor, relate how they have opted forForth Shift's microcomputer software after trying mainframe-based,centralized CIM.andP;  Forth Shift's manufacturing resource planningsystem coordinates production schedules with customer orders andinventory controls.andP;  Eastman Kodak Co, for example, has installedabout 50 microcomputer-based control systems at manufacturingsites after spending $66 million on a centralized CIM system.andO;Kodak's Jack Philbin says that the decentralization process is noteasy, and that it requires a complete rethinking of themanufacturing process.andP;  Forth Shift's Jerry Bowman estimates that70 percent of current CIM systems are minicomputer based, while 10percent reside on mainframes and 20 percent run on microcomputers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Forth Shift (products)Eastman Kodak Co. (production control).andO;Ticker:    EK.andO;Topic:     Computer-Integrated ManufacturingManufacturingResource ManagementSoftwareDecentralization.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>